## Phase 5. FIX ANALYSIS

### 5.1 What the problem is:
When `req.socket` is `null` (which can happen in certain situations, e.g., with webpack-dev-server), the middleware tries to access `req.socket.server` which results in `undefined`/`null`. This value is then passed to `catchUpgradeRequest(server)` which tries to call `server.on('upgrade', ...)` on null/undefined, causing:
```
TypeError: Cannot read property 'on' of null
```

### 5.2 Where the problem is located:
In `/workspace/http-proxy-middleware/src/http-proxy-middleware.ts`, line 106-109:
```typescript
if (this.proxyOptions.ws === true) {
    // use initial request to access the server object to subscribe to http upgrade event
    this.catchUpgradeRequest(server);
}
```

The `server` variable (from line 94) can be `undefined` when `req.socket` is null, but there's no null check before calling `catchUpgradeRequest(server)`.

Also need to update the corresponding compiled `dist/http-proxy-middleware.js` (line 92-95):
```javascript
if (this.proxyOptions.ws === true) {
    // use initial request to access the server object to subscribe to http upgrade event
    this.catchUpgradeRequest(server);
}
```

### 5.3 How to reproduce:
When `req.socket` is null (for instance in webpack-dev-server), accessing `req.socket.server` returns `undefined`, and calling `.on()` on `undefined` throws `TypeError: Cannot read property 'on' of null`.

### 5.4 Best practices:
- Always null-check before calling methods on objects that may be null/undefined
- The `serverOnCloseSubscribed` already has this guard (`if (server && !this.serverOnCloseSubscribed)`), so the same pattern should be applied to `catchUpgradeRequest`

### 5.5 How to fix:
Add a null check: change `if (this.proxyOptions.ws === true)` to `if (server && this.proxyOptions.ws === true)` in the source file and corresponding dist file.

